transcript_text: A declaration of peace between the leaders of Thailand and Cambodia, and a diplomatic accomplishment for President Donald Trump. For several days in July, these two kingdoms in Southeast Asia engaged in deadly fighting. The Thai and Cambodian militaries battled each other across stretches of their long, contested border, killing dozens and displacing some 200,000 people. Cambodia fired rockets while a tie of 16s carried out airstrikes. It was the worst violence between these two countries in generations. In late July, a lull in the fighting, after Trump declared, amid threats of imposing high tariffs, that Cambodia and Thailand agreed to immediately meet and quickly work out a ceasefire and ultimately peace. The next day, with the help of U.S. mediation, Cambodia's Prime Minister met his Thai counterpart in Malaysia to agree to a temporary ceasefire. Sunday's signing ceremony in Kuala Lumpur builds on those initial peace gains and marks a diplomatic victory for Trump and his often stated commitment to conflict resolution.
title: Thailand and Cambodia sign peace agreement
description: US President Donald Trump oversaw the signing of a peace accord between the leaders of Cambodia and Thailand on Sunday in Malaysia, building on a truce signed several months ago following deadly border clashes. title: Nepal PM KP Oli resigns as anti-corruption protests escalate | BBC News India
description:
Nepal‚Äôs prime minister KP Sharma Oli has resigned as anti-corruption protests across the country escalated on Tuesday.

Though the protests were triggered by the social media ban, there has been widespread frustration with the government over the perceived lack of action to tackle corruption. Thousands took to the streets on Tuesday, even as a curfew was put in place after 19 people were killed in clashes between police and protesters on Monday. At least two more people were killed on Tuesday.

Oli took over as Prime Minister in July 2024, his fourth time in office, with the backing of the Nepali Congress Party.

The unrest is the worst in decades for the Himalayan nation.

title: The Ultimate Birthday Party #jokes #funny #isolation #awkward #comedy #darkhumor #unexpectedtwist
description:
Sam has been in business for 25 years and is finally sick of the stress. He quits his job and buys 50 acres in Alaska as far from humanity as possible. He sees the postman once a week and gets groceries once a month. Otherwise it's total peace and quiet. After six months or so of almost total isolation, someone knocks on his door. He opens it and there's a big, bearded man standing there.
"Name's Lars ...Your neighbor from forty miles away....Having a birthday party Friday ... Thought you might like to come. About 5...
"Great," says Sam, "after six months out here I'm ready to meet some local folks. Thank you."
As Lars is leaving, he stops. "Gotta warn you...There's gonna be some drinkin'."
"Not a problem... after 25 years in business, I can drink with the best of em."
Again, as he starts to leave, Lars stops. "More'n'likely gonna be some fightin' too."
Sam says, "Well, I get along with people. I'll be there. Thanks again."
Once again Lars turns from the door. "I've seen some wild sex at these parties, too."
"Now that's really not a problem," says Sam. "I've been all alone for six months! I'll definitely be there. By the way, what should I bring?"
Lars stops in the door again and says, "Whatever you want, just gonna be the two of us".

How I got here‚Ä¶

21: Graduated Vanderbilt in 3 years Magna Cum Laude, and took a fancy consulting job.
23 yrs old: Left my fancy consulting job to start a business (a gym).
24 yrs old: Opened 5 gym locations.
26 yrs old: Closed down 6th gym. Lost everything. 
26 yrs old: Got back to launching gyms (launched 33). Then, lost everything for a 2nd time.

31 yrs old: Started our family office Acquisition.com. We invest and scale companies using the $42M in distributions we had taken + the cash from the $46.2M exit.
32 yrs old: Started making free content showing how we grow companies to make real business education accessible to everyone (and) to attract business owners to invest or scale their businesses. 
34 yrs old: I became co-owner of https://Skool.com to help the many people who want to start a business online do so.

Today: Our portfolio now does $200M/yr between 10 companies. The largest doing $100M/yr the smallest doing $5M per year. Our ownership varies between 20% and 100% ownership of the companies. Many of them we invested in early and helped grow (which is how we make our money - not youtube videos).

Keep crushing. May your desires be greater than your obstacles. 

Never quit,

Alex

description:
Recently in Delhi, a controversy broke out over the city government‚Äôs handling of air pollution data. Videos circulated online showing water being sprayed around air-quality monitoring stations in certain parts of the city, especially near areas like Anand Vihar. This led to allegations that the Delhi government was trying to artificially lower pollution readings by wetting the ground around the sensors. The idea behind the claim is that spraying water can temporarily reduce dust and particulate matter in the air, which might make the air quality appear better than it actually is.

People who made these allegations pointed out that only the areas around the monitoring stations were being sprayed, while nearby roads and open spaces, which also contribute to pollution, were left untreated. They argued that this selective watering could make the air-quality data look more favorable, misleading both the public and policymakers about the true level of pollution in the city.

The Delhi government, however, denied any wrongdoing. Officials said that the sprinkling of water was part of routine anti-pollution efforts meant to reduce dust in heavily polluted zones. They also stated that the air-quality monitoring systems are automated and cannot be manually tampered with. According to them, the timing of water-spraying near the stations was coincidental and not an attempt to manipulate data.

This incident has raised questions about transparency and trust in how air pollution is being managed in Delhi. While spraying water is a legitimate method to control dust, doing it selectively near sensors can create doubts about the integrity of the data. Many people believe that a more transparent approach, with clear reporting on when and where such activities take place, is necessary to maintain public confidence and ensure that pollution-control efforts are genuinely helping improve air quality, not just improving the numbers.

Ali Siddiq is a stand-up comedian, public speaker, and writer out of Houston. Ali‚Äôs unique style of stand-up began behind the walls of incarceration, an incubator for interesting experiences and good stories.  
 
People received their first taste of Ali Siddiq when he appeared on HBO's DEF COMEDY JAM and LIVE FROM GOTHAM, and in 2013 he was named Comedy Central's "#1 Comic to Watch".  In 2014, Ali impressed comedy enthusiasts by displaying his ability to captivate an audience with his "Mexicans Got On Boots" tale, descriptive storytelling, with over 15 million views, of a prison riot on THIS IS NOT HAPPENING, the first of three appearances.  His stories continued with his HALF HOUR special, which premiered on Comedy Central in the fall of 2016.  Immediately following the premiere of that special, Comedy Central offered Ali an hour-special where he performed for inmates live in a Texas jail, sending Ali back to where it all started. The hour special, Ali Siddiq: It‚Äôs Bigger Than These Bars, premiered in February 2018 on Comedy Central.  In 2019, Ali could be seen as a Top 5 finalist on NBC‚Äôs BRING THE FUNNY. title: Ricky Gervais is FURIOUS with UK Government Censorship! #comedy #funny #standup
description:
Ricky Gervais is one of the most distinctive and influential comedic voices of the 21st century, renowned for his sharp wit, unapologetic humor, and boundary-pushing approach to entertainment. Born on June 25, 1961, in Reading, England, Gervais grew up in a working-class family, the youngest of four children. His upbringing deeply shaped his worldview and comedic sensibilities, grounding his humor in a blend of everyday realism, skepticism, and social commentary. Before achieving fame, he attended University College London, where he studied philosophy a subject that would later influence his reflections on human nature, morality, and the absurdities of modern life.

Gervais‚Äôs rise to international prominence began with 'The Office' (2001‚Äì2003), a groundbreaking mockumentary series that he co-created, co-wrote, directed, and starred in as the cringe-inducing yet oddly endearing David Brent. The show was an instant critical success, redefining television comedy with its deadpan tone, realistic documentary style, and unflinching portrayal of workplace monotony and human insecurity. 'The Office' became a global phenomenon, inspiring numerous international adaptations including the hugely successful American version starring Steve Carell. The show earned Gervais and co-creator Stephen Merchant widespread acclaim, including Golden Globes and BAFTA Awards, and cemented Gervais as a creative pioneer.

Following the success of 'The Office', Gervais continued to expand his creative range. He and Merchant collaborated again on 'Extras' (2005‚Äì2007), a series that explored fame, ego, and artistic integrity through the eyes of struggling actor Andy Millman. Known for its celebrity cameos and biting satire, 'Extras' further demonstrated Gervais‚Äôs talent for blending humor with pathos. He later ventured into stand-up comedy, where his style marked by bold social commentary, dark humor, and fearless candor garnered both praise and controversy. His specials, such as 'Animals', 'Humanity', and 'SuperNature', showcased his ability to provoke thought while making audiences laugh, tackling topics ranging from religion and fame to animal rights and political correctness.

Beyond television and stand-up, Gervais has made significant contributions to film and digital media. His roles in films like 'Ghost Town' (2008), 'The Invention of Lying' (2009), and 'Cemetery Junction' (2010) highlight his flair for combining comedy with emotional depth and philosophical insight. In recent years, his Netflix series 'After Life' (2019‚Äì2022) marked a creative and emotional turning point. The show, which explores grief, kindness, and the search for meaning after loss, resonated deeply with audiences and critics alike. Balancing dark humor with profound empathy, 'After Life' displayed a more mature and introspective side of Gervais‚Äôs artistry, earning widespread acclaim for its honesty and humanity.

Gervais is also well-known for his outspoken views and unfiltered public persona. As a frequent host of the Golden Globe Awards, he became notorious for his scathing monologues targeting Hollywood elites, celebrity culture, and hypocrisy within the entertainment industry. His fearless approach to comedy often walking the line between satire and offense has sparked debates about the limits of humor and free speech. Gervais himself has consistently defended the right to joke about any subject, arguing that comedy should challenge comfort zones and encourage critical thinking.

Beyond entertainment, Gervais is a passionate advocate for animal rights and humanitarian causes. He uses his platform to raise awareness about animal cruelty and environmental issues, supporting organizations such as PETA and the Humane Society. His outspoken advocacy reflects his personal values of empathy and integrity, qualities often mirrored in his work despite his acerbic comedic style.

Today, Ricky Gervais stands as a defining figure in modern comedy one who has reshaped the landscape of television, stand-up, and cultural discourse. Through his fearless humor, intellectual curiosity, and deep understanding of human vulnerability, he continues to challenge audiences to laugh, think, and question the world around them. Whether as a comedian, writer, actor, or social commentator, Gervais remains a rare figure who fuses irreverence with authenticity, leaving an enduring legacy in entertainment and beyond.

Updated Sep 12, 2025:
Back in the early days of the church, they would stone you for standing up for your beliefs.
Now, you can get shot.

.......

When the first martyr Stephen was stoned in Acts 7, he cried out:
"Lord, do not hold this sin against them.‚Äù (Acts 7:60, ESV)

I didn‚Äôt know Charlie Kirk personally ‚Äî but based on what I‚Äôve seen,
he grew in his faith during his public life and became quite respectful toward many (if not most?) of those who disagreed with him.

I want to believe, if he had the chance, he would have said the same thing Stephen did.
(And this is what I hope for my own attitude if I, dmh, am ever martyred someday):
"Father, don‚Äôt hold this sin against them."

That‚Äôs the kind of man I want to believe Charlie was,
based on videos I‚Äôve seen of how kindly he treated many of his haters.

.......

Charlie wasn‚Äôt perfect. He misspoke at times ‚Äî as we humans tend to do.
He said controversial things ‚Äî but controversial things are often true.

Example:

 The resurrection of my Lord and Savior Jesus Christ
= highly controversial AND true at the same time.



Charlie‚Äôs is the kind of courage and grace we need more of, in my opinion.
‚Äì dmh

In an episode of Club Random (see my channel for 2 short clips), Charlie Kirk joins Bill Maher
for a wide-ranging conversation that aired on April 20, 2025.

At one point, Charlie and Bill briefly discuss the need for personal security ‚Äî
a passing moment that now feels sobering in retrospect.

4 months and 21 days later, Charlie was shot and killed.

.......

Reports as of Sep 12 say the bullet casings at the scene were engraved with:

‚ÄúHey, fascist! CATCH!‚Äù

Lyrics from the anti-fascist song ‚ÄúBella Ciao‚Äù

‚ÄúIf you read this, you are gay LMAO‚Äù

‚ÄúNotices bulge, OWO what‚Äôs this?‚Äù


.......

Whether you agreed with Charlie or not,
this wasn‚Äôt just about politics ‚Äî
it was about the cost of standing up for your beliefs
in an increasingly volatile culture.

üôè Pray for God's will to be done with justice for Charlie Kirk's family.

üïäÔ∏è May Charlie rest in peace.

God is a God of mercy,
but also a God of justice.

Don‚Äôt take freedom of speech for granted (preaching to myself)

Jesus is Lord.

title: Syrian Swimmer returns home after 10 years to find her house destroyed
description:
UNHCR Goodwill Ambassador and former Syrian swimmer Yusra Mardini returned home to Syria to find most of her neighbourhood in Daraya destroyed, including the building where she once lived.

Located in the suburbs of Damascus, Daraya was repeatedly targeted by Russian and former Syrian government air strikes during 14 years of conflict.

While crossing the Aegean Sea from Turkey to Greece in 2015, Yusra, along with her sister and two others, saved the lives of everyone in their dinghy by swimming beside the boat for several hours, navigating it to safety after the engine had failed‚Äîa story that inspired the 2022 Netflix film The Swimmers.

After finding refuge in Germany, Mardini went on to compete as a member of the first-ever Refugee Olympic Team at the 2016 Olympics in Rio de Janeiro and again at the Tokyo Games.

description:
A class professor was giving a lecture on company slogans and was asking his students if they were familiar with them.

"Joe," he asked, "which company has the slogan, 'come fly the friendly skies'?"

Joe answered the correct airline.

"Brenda, can you tell me which company has the slogan, "Don't leave home without it?"

Brenda answered the correct credit card company with no difficulty.

"Now John, Tell me which company bears the slogan, 'Just do it'?"

And John answered, "Mom...."
